e. And I hope to be alive when there&apos;s a cure for HIV for everyone.\"</p> <p>-30-</p>\n   ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,'News','News',NULL),(186,0,0,'Hey Ocean!&apos;s album that almost wasn&apos;t','text/html','http://cupwire.hotink.net/articles/53142','Canada',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,12,'\n<p><strong></strong></h2><p>Arts</strong></p><p><strong>Doug Johnson - The Griff (Grant MacEwan University)</strong></p><p>EDMONTON (CUP) - Remember the plane scene in <em>Almost Famous</em> where the fictional band Stillwater is driven to the brink of death by an electrical storm, whereupon the band members end up having - and solving - a major existential crisis all in the span of a few minutes?</p> <p>That&apos;s exactly the image that went through my mind when I sat down to talk with Ashleigh Ball of Hey Ocean!, a Vancouver based classic-pop trio currently touring Canada in support of their new album, <em>IS</em>.</p> <hr /> <p><a href=\"http://www.thegriff.ca/2012/09/how-it-almost-wasnt-what-it-is/?utm_source=rss&amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;utm_campaign=how-it-almost-wasnt-what-it-is\"><strong>Click here for the original article from The Griff</strong></a></p> <hr /> <p>Recently signed to Universal, the band has achieved what few other Canadian bands ever will. But it wasn&apos;t easy. It took hard work; it took late nights; it took, you know, a very Stillwater-esque existential crisis (minus, presumably, the crashing plane, the confessions of homosexuality, the acid, etc.).</p> <p>\"There were a lot of really intense moments,\" says Ball. \"Moments where we didn&apos;t know what was going to happen, the thought of potentially breaking up, and yeah ... It was just kind of a roller-coaster ride making that album.\"</p> <p>The album, inspired by an eclectic mix of pop gods both old and new - Rhianna, Katy Perry, Michael Jackson, Fleetwood Mac and Paul Simon were all influences, says Ball - strives for a markedly \"classic pop\" feel, a genre shift that may or may not be at odds with the band&apos;s history and reputation as an indie outfit.</p> <p>\"On my part there was a lot of fear involved in going this more pop-y route and just going for it and getting over that and not being afraid. There&apos;s so many different ways you can take a song or that you could go as an artist. I think I was afraid of either letting our fans down, or letting myself down, or letting the guys down, or whoever it was ... We didn&apos;t want to feel like we were selling out or making something that wasn&apos;t truly us,\" says Ball.</p> <p>This trepidation, along with the challenge of working with a new producer, was what ultimately led to the band&apos;s very own Stillwater moment - a moment, Ball says, where they were struggling with who they were. In the end, it was an experience they came out the better for: it was only after the album was released that they were signed by Universal.</p> <p>Since the signing, they landed an esteemed gig playing at the Toronto International Film Festival alongside Yukon Blonde, Dan Mangan, Humans and PS I Love You, and are now on a cross-country tour.</p> <p>\"We want to keep it exciting, we want to keep people moving and interacting and dancing and, you know, crying maybe,\" Ball said with a laugh. \"Well maybe not - depending. But yeah, it&apos;s always really fun for us. I love performing for the audience. We like to have as much fun as we can out there and bring our best to each performance.\"</p> <p>As for the music they&apos;ll be playing, you needn&apos;t look further than the album&apos;s title, <em>IS</em>.</p> <p>\"It represents the three of us - not too pushy and just kind of is . . . We&apos;re making music that is what it is. On our next album it&apos;s probably not going to sound anything like this one,\" says Ball. \"It was a moment in time. We wanted to be to the point. Yeah, we made music that is what it is at this point in time.\"</p> <p>-30-</p>\n   ',1348774471,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Thu, 20 Sep 2012 18:20:00 -0400',NULL,'Canadian University Press newswire RSS feed',NULL,'\n<p><strong></strong></h2><p>Arts</strong></p><p><strong>Doug Johnson - The Griff (Grant MacEwan University)</strong></p><p>EDMONTON (CUP) - Remember the plane scene in <em>Almost Famous</em> where the fictional band Stillwater is driven to the brink of death by an electrical storm, whereupon the band members end up having - and solving - a major existential crisis all in the span of a few minutes?</p> <p>That&apos;s exactly the image that went through my mind when I sat down to talk with Ashleigh Ball of Hey Ocean!, a Vancouver based classic-pop trio currently touring Canada in support of their new album, <em>IS</em>.</p> <hr /> <p><a href=\"http://www.thegriff.ca/2012/09/how-it-almost-wasnt-what-it-is/?utm_source=rss&amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;utm_campaign=how-it-almost-wasnt-what-it-is\"><strong>Click here for the original article from The Griff</strong></a></p> <hr /> <p>Recently signed to Universal, the band has achieved what few other Canadian bands ever will. But it wasn&apos;t easy. It took hard work; it took late nights; it took, you know, a very Stillwater-esque existential crisis (minus, presumably, the crashing plane, the confessions of homosexuality, the acid, etc.).</p> <p>\"There were a lot of really intense moments,\" says Ball. \"Moments where we didn&apos;t know what was going to happen, the thought of potentially breaking up, and yeah ... It was just kind of a roller-coaster ride making that album.\"</p> <p>The album, inspired by an eclectic mix of pop gods both old and new - Rhianna, Katy Perry, Michael Jackson, Fleetwood Mac and Paul Simon were all influences, says Ball - strives for a markedly \"classic pop\" feel, a genre shift that may or may not be at odds with the band&apos;s history and reputation as an indie outfit.</p> <p>\"On my part there was a lot of fear involved in going this more pop-y route and just going for it and getting over that and not being afraid. There&apos;s so many different ways you can take a song or that you could go as an artist. I think I was afraid of either letting our fans down, or letting myself down, or letting the guys down, or whoever it was ... We didn&apos;t want to feel like we were selling out or making something that wasn&apos;t truly us,\" says Ball.</p> <p>This trepidation, along with the challenge of working with a new producer, was what ultimately led to the band&apos;s very own Stillwater moment - a moment, Ball says, where they were struggling with who they were. In the end, it was an experience they came out the better for: it was only after the album was released that they were signed by Universal.</p> <p>Since the signing, they landed an esteemed gig playing at the Toronto International Film Festival alongside Yukon Blonde, Dan Mangan, Humans and PS I Love You, and are now on a cross-country tour.</p> <p>\"We want to keep it exciting, we want to keep people moving and interacting and dancing and, you know, crying maybe,\" Ball said with a laugh. \"Well maybe not - depending. But yeah, it&apos;s always really fun for us. I love performing for the audience. We like to have as much fun as we can out there and bring our best to each performance.\"</p> <p>As for the music they&apos;ll be playing, you needn&apos;t look further than the album&apos;s title, <em>IS</em>.</p> <p>\"It represents the three of us - not too pushy and just kind of is . . . We&apos;re making music that is what it is. On our next album it&apos;s probably not going to sound anything like this one,\" says Ball. \"It was a moment in time. We wanted to be to the point. Yeah, we made music that is what it is at this point in time.\"</p> <p>-30-</p>\n   ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'none',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Fresh',NULL,'News','News',NULL),(187,0,0,'Clicking with Vancouver&apos;s indie gaming scene','text/html','http://cupwire.hotink.net/articles/53141','Canada',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,12,'\n<p><strong></strong></h2><p>Arts</strong></p><p><strong>Matt Meuse - The Ubyssey (University of British Columbia)</strong></p><p>VANCOUVER (CUP) - Kimberly Voll has been a gamer since the first time she watched her dad and uncle play Parsec on a TI-99/4A in the early 1980s.</p> <p>\"It had this synthesizer add-on, which at the time was mind-blowing technology, but it would talk! It would say things like, &apos;Nice shot, pilot, time to refuel,&apos;\" she said. She was two or three years old. \"My little head was just blown away by this. I just could not get enough of it.</p> <hr /> <p><a href=\"http://ubyssey.ca/features/our-campus-k-voll/\"><strong>Click here for the original article from The Ubyssey</strong></a></p> <hr /> <p>\"It started this deep-seated love of video games and video game-related technology, and I started playing basically then, and never stopped.\"</p> <p>Years later, Voll is still just as enthusiastic about video games and other interactive media. After six years as a computer science faculty member at UBC, she now teaches at the Centre for Digital Media, a master&apos;s program powered by a collaboration between UBC, SFU, Emily Carr University and BCIT.</p> <p>\"[Students] get a lot of practical experience,\" she said. \"They&apos;re really functioning for part of that time as almost like their own little company.\"</p> <p>In addition to student-pitched projects, the program gives students hands-on experience through partnerships with a number of Vancouver video game developers, a scene that Voll is very active in herself.</p> <p>In January 2012, she organized and ran the Vancouver Global Game Jam, an event where teams create games over a 48-hour period. The event drew about 150 participants, including both students and professionals.</p> <p>\"Ours is one of the largest [game jams] in the world,\" she said. \"It&apos;s a really awesome opportunity for students who want to know a little bit more about the development process to work really closely with industry veterans on real projects.\"</p> <p>But the benefit isn&apos;t just in networking, it&apos;s also practical experience. \"I mean, they&apos;re producing real games,\" she said. \"They actually get games done in that weekend.\"</p> <p>Voll describes Vancouver as a hub of the video game industry, particularly for indie developers. While larger \"triple-A\" companies like Ubisoft may be leaving, the city is teeming with smaller studios eager to make their mark, as events like the Global Game Jam demonstrate.</p> <p>Voll is part of one such endeavour herself, moonlighting as the lead developer for the Vancouver-based PepperDev Studios. Their first game, an iOS title called Hungry Fins, is currently in the works after a Kickstarter campaign successfully raised $8,000 to fund its development.</p> <p>\"We&apos;re working on this sort of as a second and in some cases third job, [and] it became obvious that we weren&apos;t really well-positioned to spend all of the time that is required to do a lot of the other funding routes, like [venture capital] funding,\" she said. \"The Kickstarter made that possible.\"</p> <p>Crowdsourced funding tools like Kickstarter have become a popular way for game developers to attract funding, particularly after the success of Tim Schafer&apos;s Double Fine Adventure in early 2012, but that popularity can be a double-edged sword for smaller studios.</p> <p>\"In some ways, that [makes] it a lot harder for us, because we&apos;re not a big sexy project, we&apos;re this little game company that nobody has heard of making this little thing,\" she said. \"But it&apos;s a really neat way to focus your project, because you have to do so much thinking and so much planning.\"</p> <p>Indie games may lack the multi-million dollar pizzazz of big-name blockbusters like Borderlands 2, a game Voll is particularly excited for. But Voll argues that indie games with smaller budgets, like Mark of the Ninja, can be just as enthralling.</p> <p>\"I think there&apos;s something more fundamental [than impressive graphics] to what makes a successful game,\" she said. \"You see the love and the passion that goes into the production of these [indie] games, and it&apos;s phenomenal. These are life opuses.\"</p> <p>In case there was any doubt, Voll is a gamer through and through, and she makes no bones about it. But it isn&apos;t always easy.</p> <p>\"I just like games. I am a gamer, and I identify as a gamer, not some weird category, not somebody who likes somebody else&apos;s games,\" she said.</p> <p>\"I don&apos;t want to be identified - and I find this happens a lot - as a &apos;girl gamer,&apos;\" she said, making air quotes with her fingers. \"I feel like I get shoved into one of two categories: I&apos;m either a gamer who likes girly games, or I&apos;m a girl gamer who happens to like guys&apos; games.\"</p> <p>Voll wants to erase the distinction between the two. \"Since when do guys own these games?\" she said. \"What we need is an environment where women feel welcome. And that&apos;s not creating artificial environments, that&apos;s just: you&apos;re welcome to be a gamer, to love what you love.</p> <p>\"We&apos;re all just gamers.\"</p> <p>-30-</p>\n   ',1348774472,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Thu, 20 Sep 2012 18:08:00 -0400',NULL,'Canadian University Press newswire RSS feed',NULL,'\n<p><strong></strong></h2><p>Arts</strong></p><p><strong>Matt Meuse - The Ubyssey (University of British Columbia)</strong></p><p>VANCOUVER (CUP) - Kimberly Voll has been a gamer since the first time she watched her dad and uncle play Parsec on a TI-99/4A in the early 1980s.</p> <p>\"It had this synthesizer add-on, which at the time was mind-blowing technology, but it would talk! It would say things like, &apos;Nice shot, pilot, time to refuel,&apos;\" she said. She was two or three years old. \"My little head was just blown away by this. I just could not get enough of it.</